      </div>
    </header>

    <section class="guide-body">

      <p>
        When a business broker tells you your business is worth "3 times earnings," they are referring
        to a valuation multiple. Understanding what that multiple means - where it comes from, what drives
        it up or down, and why it varies dramatically by industry - is the difference between going into
        a sale negotiation informed and going in blind.
      </p>
      <p>
        This guide uses real multiple data from {{ site.transactionCount }}+ closed transactions across
        63 industries to explain how multiples work in practice - not in theory.
      </p>

      <h2>What Is a Valuation Multiple?</h2>
      <p>
        A valuation multiple is a multiplier applied to your annual SDE (Seller's Discretionary Earnings)
        to estimate the market value of your business. The formula is simple:
      </p>
      <div class="formula-block">
        <p><strong>Business Value = Annual SDE × Industry Multiple</strong></p>
      </div>
      <p>
        If your business generates $250,000 in SDE and the median multiple for your industry is 3.0×,
        the estimated market value is $750,000. The multiple is the market's collective judgment about
        how much a dollar of your business's earnings is worth to a buyer.
      </p>

      <h2>Where Multiples Come From</h2>
      <p>
        Multiples are not invented - they are observed. Mainstreet Benchmark's industry multiples are
        derived from {{ site.transactionCount }}+ closed transactions reported to BizBuySell, CoStar Group's
        business-for-sale marketplace, across Q1 {{ site.dataCoverageStart }} through Q4 {{ site.dataCoverageEnd }}.
        These are actual sale prices, not asking prices. The lower quartile, median, and upper quartile
        multiples represent the distribution of real deals.
      </p>
      <p>
        A car wash that sold for $997,000 on $200,000 SDE paid a 4.99× multiple. An HVAC company
        that sold for $634,000 on $200,000 SDE paid a 3.17× multiple. A restaurant that sold for
        $430,000 on $200,000 SDE paid a 2.15× multiple. These are the data points that produce the
        median multiples you see in the <a href="/">valuation calculator</a>.
      </p>

      <h2>Why Multiples Vary by Industry</h2>
      <p>
        The multiple reflects what buyers will pay for a dollar of earnings in a specific industry  -
        which depends on perceived risk, earnings quality, and growth potential. Three concrete examples:
      </p>

      <h3>Car Washes: 4.99× Median</h3>
      <p>
        Car washes - specifically express exterior operations with unlimited membership programs - command
        near-5× multiples because the revenue model is fundamentally different from most small businesses.
        A 1,000-member unlimited wash club generating $35/month produces $420,000 in annual recurring
        revenue with predictable churn, minimal labor (2–4 staff members), and no meaningful owner
        involvement required. Buyers are paying a premium for the membership program as much as the physical
        asset. The <a href="/valuation/car-wash/">full car wash valuation data</a> covers all formats,
        including self-service bays which trade near the 3.5× floor.
      </p>

      <h3>HVAC Services: 3.17× Median</h3>
      <p>
        HVAC companies occupy the middle of the multiple range because they have strong recurring revenue
        potential (service contracts, maintenance agreements) but also meaningful owner dependency and
        technician risk. A well-run HVAC company where the owner manages rather than turns wrenches  -
        with 60%+ revenue from service contracts - trades in the upper quartile (3.5×+). A shop where
        the owner is the primary technician trades near the floor (2.5×) because the buyer must price in
        the cost of replacing that skill. See <a href="/valuation/hvac-services/">HVAC valuation data</a>.
      </p>

      <h3>Restaurants: 2.15× Median</h3>
      <p>
        Restaurants trade at a discount to most Main Street businesses for well-documented reasons:
        high owner and staff involvement, lease dependency (lose the location and you lose the business),
        food cost volatility, health code risk, and historically high failure rates. SBA lenders apply
        stricter underwriting to restaurant acquisitions. The upper quartile (2.5×+) applies to
        well-established restaurants with long lease terms, documented systems, and owner-independent
        operations. See <a href="/valuation/restaurant/">restaurant valuation data</a>.
      </p>

      <h2>What Drives the Multiple Up</h2>
      <p>
        Across all industries, the factors that move a business from the lower quartile to the upper quartile
        of its multiple range are consistent:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Recurring revenue:</strong> Service contracts, subscriptions, memberships, and maintenance
          agreements generate predictable forward revenue. Buyers pay more for certainty.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Low owner involvement:</strong> A business that runs via documented systems and trained
          staff - where the owner works on the business rather than in it - is more valuable and more
          transferable. The <a href="/">calculator</a> applies +0.20× for low owner involvement.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Diversified customer base:</strong> No single customer representing more than 15% of revenue
          means no single customer departure can materially impair the business. +0.10× adjustment.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Revenue growth:</strong> A business growing 20%+ per year signals market momentum.
          +0.30× adjustment for strong growth in the calculator.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Clean financials:</strong> Three years of consistent tax returns with well-documented
          add-backs accelerate diligence and build buyer confidence.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h2>What Drives the Multiple Down</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>High owner involvement:</strong> The most common discount factor. Buyers discount for
          key-person risk - the cost of replacing the owner's labor and relationships. −0.20× adjustment.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Declining revenue:</strong> Sellers who cannot explain a revenue decline face buyers
          who price the uncertainty directly into their offer. −0.25× adjustment.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Customer concentration:</strong> One customer representing 40%+ of revenue is a deal
          risk that buyers and SBA lenders scrutinize closely. −0.25× adjustment.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Lease risk:</strong> A business with a lease expiring within 12 months, no renewal option,
          or an uncooperative landlord faces buyers who walk or demand significant price concessions.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Deferred maintenance:</strong> Equipment that will require near-term capital expenditure
          becomes a direct price deduction in buyer offers - they will discount for the replacement cost.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h2>The Adjustment Model</h2>
      <p>
        The <a href="/">valuation calculator</a> applies the following adjustments to the industry median:
      </p>
      <div class="data-table-wrap">
        <table class="data-table">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th scope="col">Factor</th>
              <th scope="col">Selection</th>
              <th scope="col">Adjustment</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Revenue Trend</td><td>Growing 20%+</td><td>+0.30×</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Revenue Trend</td><td>Growing 10–20%</td><td>+0.15×</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Revenue Trend</td><td>Flat (±5%)</td><td>0×</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Revenue Trend</td><td>Declining</td><td>−0.25×</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Owner Involvement</td><td>Low (systematized)</td><td>+0.20×</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Owner Involvement</td><td>Moderate</td><td>0×</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Owner Involvement</td><td>High (owner-dependent)</td><td>−0.20×</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Customer Concentration</td><td>Diverse</td><td>+0.10×</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Customer Concentration</td><td>Concentrated</td><td>−0.25×</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <p>
        The best-case scenario (+0.30 + 0.20 + 0.10 = +0.60×) and the worst-case scenario
        (−0.25 − 0.20 − 0.25 = −0.70×) can swing the multiple by over 1.3×. On a $300,000 SDE business
        in an industry with a 3.0× median, that swing equals $390,000 in valuation difference
        ($1,080,000 best vs. $690,000 worst). This is why conditions matter as much as earnings.
      </p>

      <h2>The Revenue Multiple as a Secondary Check</h2>
      <p>
        For industries where revenue is more predictable than earnings (e.g., recurring service businesses),
        buyers sometimes apply a revenue multiple as a secondary reference. The calculator shows both:
        the SDE-based estimate (primary) and a revenue-based estimate derived from the industry's average
        revenue multiple. For most Main Street businesses, the SDE-based figure governs - the revenue
        multiple is a sanity check, not a competing method.
      </p>

      <h2>How to Use the Multiple in Negotiation</h2>
      <p>
        Knowing your industry's multiple range entering negotiations means you can evaluate offers
        rationally rather than emotionally. An offer at 2.5× SDE when your industry median is 3.0× is
        a below-market offer that deserves negotiation. An offer at 2.5× when your business has high owner
        involvement and declining revenue is actually reasonable - the buyer is applying appropriate risk
        discounts.
      </p>
      <p>
        The most common mistake sellers make is comparing their offer to the highest multiple they have
        heard about, rather than the realistic multiple for their specific business conditions. The
        what-if simulation in the <a href="/">valuation calculator</a> lets you model exactly how
        improving your conditions would change the number before you list.
      </p>

    </section>

